niversal prejudice’s neurological and social origins and its wide-ranging, pernicious consequences, from unnoticed hate crimes to aporophobia’s threat to democracy. It sheds new light on today’s rampant anti-immigrant feeling, which Cortina argues is better understood as aporophobia than xenophobia. We reject migrants not because of their origin, race, or ethnicity but because they seem to bring problems while offering nothing of value. And this is unforgivable in societies that enshrine economic exchange as the supreme value while forgetting that we can’t create communities worth living in without dignity, generosity, and compassion for all. Yet there is hope, and Cortina explains how we can overcome the moral, social, and political disaster of aporophobia through education and democratic institutions, and how poverty itself can be eradicated if we choose.In a world of migrant crises and economic inequality, Aporophobia is essential for understanding and confronting one of the most serious problems of the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPoorxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPovertyxMoral and ethical aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aAggression.  aAltruism.  aAmartya Sen.  aAntisemitism.  aAwareness.  aCharles Darwin.  aCitizenship.  aClimate change.  aConscience.  aContempt.  aCriticism.  aEconomy.  aElectric car.  aElectricity.  aEmotion.  aEthics.  aEthnic group.  aFossil fuel.  aFreedom of speech.  aGlaucon.  aGreenhouse gas.  aHate crime.  aHate speech.  aHatred.  aHeat pump.  aHomo economicus.  aHomophobia.  aHospitality.  aHumiliation.  aIdeology.  aIncitement.  aIngroups and outgroups.  aInstitution.  aIslamophobia.  aLegislation.  aMisogyny.  aMorality.  aMotivation.  aNitrogen.  a